  "slug": "the-superman-movie-rankings",
  "title": "The Superman Movie Rankings",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Rob Mahoney",
    "Van Lathan"
  ],
  "published": "2025-07-14",
  "runtimeMin": 118,
  "format": "Rob Mahoney and Van Lathan join Sean Fennessey to talk James Gunn's Superman, then rank all 11 Superman movies from Donner to Corenswet.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "James Gunn's Superman, the box office, and the DCU",
      "note": "before the rankings",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Superman",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Opened to $217M worldwide ($122M domestic), solid at home but light in Europe, for a movie the panel reads as openly about immigration and Gaza. All three praise the Corenswet/Brosnahan/Hoult casting and Gunn putting Superman in a world built to fit him. The bar for whether the DCU works, they agree, is Clayface."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "ranking",
      "heading": "The Superman Movie Rankings",
      "note": "worst to best on air; No. 1 first here",
      "subject": "Superman",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Superman (1978)",
          "year": 1978,
          "note": "No. 1. 'The father of all the other films': patient zero for big-budget superhero storytelling, and Reeve is Superman. Sits just below Jaws and Star Wars in the '70s pantheon."
        },
        {
          "title": "Superman II",
          "year": 1980,
          "note": "No. 2. The Lester theatrical cut. Van makes the case it's better than the original: more happening, sharper Lois-and-Clark chemistry. The panel keeps it at 2 on Sean's 'importance' grounds."
        },
        {
          "title": "Superman",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "No. 3. The Corenswet/Gunn film, already in the pantheon on first watch. Brosnahan's Lois might 'snatch the crown' from Margot Kidder; not as good as the '78 original, and that's no knock."
        },
        {
          "title": "Superman II: The Richard Donner Cut",
          "year": 2006,
          "note": "No. 4. Sharper, more adversarial Lois and the blanks-gunshot reveal, but it recycles the spin-the-Earth-back ending and never cohered as a finished film."
        },
        {
          "title": "Superman III",
          "year": 1983,
          "note": "No. 5. Ends up here by default. A Richard Pryor comedy that keeps forgetting it's a Superman movie; the junkyard fight between good and evil Clark is the highlight."
        },
        {
          "title": "Zack Snyder's Justice League",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "No. 6. Beats Superman IV on ambition and scale: high fantasy inside a superhero movie, plus the Knightmare coda the panel wishes had been its own film."
        },
        {
          "title": "Superman IV: The Quest for Peace",
          "year": 1987,
          "note": "No. 7. Cannon Films schlock and Reeve's nuclear-disarmament passion project: Nuclear Man, Gene Hackman dubbing his voice, 90 minutes. Van's sentimental favorite, ranked honestly."
        },
        {
          "title": "Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "No. 8. Only makes narrative sense in the Ultimate Cut. Affleck's Batman is the best thing in it; the Martha ending is 'heinous.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Man of Steel",
          "year": 2013,
          "note": "No. 9. Snyder 'doesn't get Superman': the Metropolis-leveling punch-fest and the snapped neck. Russell Crowe's Jor-El and the Krypton opening are the salvage. Sean's most-hated of the lot."
        },
        {
          "title": "Superman Returns",
          "year": 2006,
          "note": "No. 10. Singer's inert nostalgia-porn sequel to Superman II: Routh and Bosworth have anti-chemistry, and its five-years-gone premise doesn't hold. Roundly disliked."
        },
        {
          "title": "Justice League",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "Last. The Whedon theatrical cut, 'in the running for the worst movie of its scale ever made.'"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
